message:
fix(codegen): Add 'try' when wrapping error union calls in PyValue.from()

Fixed a critical bug where function calls returning error unions were
wrapped in PyValue.from() without 'try', causing the error union type
to be passed instead of the unwrapped value.

Before (BROKEN):
  const g: runtime.PyValue = runtime.PyValue.from(gcd(allocator, den, num));
  // gcd returns !i64, but no 'try' means error union passed to PyValue.from()
  // PyValue.from() doesn't handle error unions → returns .none
  // Subsequent arithmetic uses .none instead of actual value!

After (FIXED):
  const g: runtime.PyValue = runtime.PyValue.from(try gcd(allocator, den, num));
  // 'try' unwraps !i64 → i64 before passing to PyValue.from()

Impact:
- Rat.__init__ in test_binop.py now works correctly
- test_constructor: FAIL → PASS (gcd normalization now works)
- 9 other Rat tests still fail (arithmetic operators) but constructor works

Root cause: assign.zig line 1358 called genExpr() without checking if
the value expression is a call returning an error union.

Fix: Added check at line 1360: emit 'try ' before genExpr() when
wrapper_opened && value is a call.

files.patch:
@@ -1354,6 +1354,13 @@ pub fn genAssign(self: *NativeCodegen, assign: ast.Node.Assign) CodegenError!voi
                 try self.emitInlineBlockEnd();
                 try self.emit(");\n");
             } else {
+                // TWO-FLOW TYPE SYSTEM: If PyValue wrapper was opened, check if value is a call
+                // that returns an error union. If so, emit 'try' to unwrap it before passing to PyValue.from()
+                // This handles cases like: g = gcd(den, num) where gcd returns !i64
+                const needs_try = is_first_assignment and wrapper_opened and assign.value.* == .call;
+                if (needs_try) {
+                    try self.emit("try ");
+                }
                 // Emit value normally
                 try self.genExpr(assign.value.*);
                 // TWO-FLOW TYPE SYSTEM: Close PyValue.from() wrapper if it was opened
